photo_description: I love taking hikes locally and hunting for mushrooms. Itâ€™s exciting to come across something new, document it, then research and identify them later. Sometimes, this leads to choice edibles. Sometimes, you learn that what you have found is best to be admired for its looks. The Amanita muscaria, commonly known as fly agaric, is a poisonous mushroom. Eating this mushroom can lead to nausea and stomach cramps at first, then eventually liver and kidney damage. If you ever have to ask if it is edible, do not eat it. Always consult an expert.

photo_description: The Dugongs of Marsha Shouna (Dugong dugon)    Dugongs are believed to be inspirations behind tales of mermaids and in parts of Indonesia they are considered reincarnations of women. The word "dugong" means lady of the sea. It's herbivorous and feed uniquely on sea grass. Their numbers are very low and in some countries they are entirely depleted due to hunting, bycatch and habitat destruction. I was extremely lucky to encounter one in Marsha Shouna on the western coast of the Red Sea, once home to thousands of dugongs but now with very few individuals. The 100 km coastline along Marsa Alam had only seven dugongs left at the time of writing.

Instagram: @danjrusso  For this shot, I really wanted to be able to practice making use of lens compression (using a higher â€œzoomâ€ lens, and getting further away from the subject making the background appear much larger than it would with, say, a portrait lens). This lens is a 70-300mm f/4 lens, and was able to make the sun in the background appear over 6x larger than normal! If you are ever taking photos in the mountains, try this method out. The mountains will fill the frame much more and appear very large behind you!  For more photos like these, follow me on instagram @danjrusso

photo_description: NGC 4565 â€“ the Needle Galaxy    Located between 30 â€“ 50 million light years away, itâ€™s the most prominent edge-on spiral galaxies we have in our view. Residing near the North Galactic Pole in the constellation Coma Berenices (named for â€œBerenice's Hair" in Latin and refers to Queen Berenice II of Egypt, who cut off her hair in gratitude to the gods for the safe return of her husband from battle), it has a spatial diameter of 140,000 light-years (Milky Way = 105,000 ly) and is estimated to contain a trillion stars (Milky Way 250-400 billion). With the darkness from a central dust lane obscuring much of the visual core of the galaxy, itâ€™s very similar to our view of the core our Milky Way, and as such is studied extensively by astronomers.
